===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|seġel}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*seglą}} (compare earlier Middle Low German {{l|gml|segel}} and later Low German {{l|nds|sail}}), cognate with Dutch {{term/t|nl|zeil}}, German {{term/t|de|Segel}}, Danish {{term/t|da|sejl}}), from pre-Germanic/Celtic ''sek-lo'' (compare Welsh {{term/t|cy|hwyl}}, Irish {{term/t|ga|séol}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*sek-}} 'to cut'. More at [[saw]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|nautical|lang=en}} A piece of [[fabric]] attached to a [[boat]] and arranged such that it causes the wind to drive the boat along. The sail may be attached to the boat via a combination of [[mast]], [[spar]]s and ropes.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Midsummer|II}}: Scene 1: 496-497
#*: When we have laugh'd to see the '''sails''' conceive / And grow big-bellied with the wanton wind;
# {{context|uncountable|lang=en}} The power harnessed by a sail or sails, or the use this power for travel or transport.
# A trip in a boat, especially a [[sailboat]].
#: ''Let's go for a '''sail'''.''
# {{context|dated|lang=en}} A sailing vessel; a vessel of any kind; a craft. Plural ''sail''.
#: ''Twenty '''sail''' were in sight.''
# The [[blade]] of a [[windmill]].
# A tower-like structure found on the dorsal (topside) surface of [[submarine]]s.
# The floating organ of [[siphonophore]]s, such as the [[Portuguese man-of-war]].
# {{context|fishing|lang=en}} A [[sailfish]].
#: ''We caught three '''sails''' today.''
# {{cx|paleontology|lang=en}} an outward projection of the {{l/en|spine}}, occurring in certain {{l/en|dinosaur|dinosaurs}} and {{l/en|synapsid|synapsids}}
# Anything resembling a sail, such as a [[wing]].
#* Spenser
#*: Like an eagle soaring / To weather his broad '''sails'''.

